Exercise 4. Using the birth weight model from the earlier exercise (birth weight of the baby as the response (in pounds) and motherâs age (in years) as the predictor, complete the following.

  1. For a one year increase in age of the mother, we expect baby weight to increase by 0.0102 pounds, on average.

  2. When age of the mother is 0 years, we expect baby weight to be 6.78 pounds, on average.

  3. No: this is extrapolation. There are no mothers in the data set who are 0 years old (this would not make any sense).

  4. The percentage of variability in baby weight that can be explained by a model with age of the mother is 0.179%.

  4. The percentage of variability in driving distance that can be explained by a model with percent fairways hit is 15.59 %.


Exercise 6.

Fitting linear model: weight ~ smoke
Â  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 7.18 0.149 48.18 2.398e-92
smokesmoker -0.4005 0.2581 -1.552 0.1229
weight m_age smoke
6.88 30 smoker
7.69 36 nonsmoker
  1. \(\hat{Y} =\) 7.1795 + -0.4005 \(smoke_{ind}\),

where \(\hat{Y}\) is predicted weight, and \(smoke_{ind}\) is equal to a \(0\) if the mother was not a smoker and a \(1\) if the mother was a smoker.

  1. 7.18 pounds.

  2. 6.78 pounds.

  3. 0.101 pounds.

  4. For mothers who do not smoke, we expect the average baby weight to be 7.1795 pounds.

  5. We expect the average baby weight for mothers who do smoke to be 0.4005 pounds less than the average baby weight for mothers who do not smoke.

  1. \(\hat{Y} =\) 16.47 + 7.669 \(test_{ind}\),

where \(\hat{Y}\) is the predicted time, and \(test_{ind}\) is equal to a \(0\) if the person was in the control test group and a \(1\) if the person was in the stroop test group.
